																						Landmann
										</a>
																	</div>
																								</figcaption>
							</div>
			</div>
</figure>
</p>

<p class="dropcap">&ldquo;So, how come you haven&rsquo;t called?&rdquo; I ask Jack while balancing the phone receiver, a bad cough, and a cup of ginger tea with honey. Outside, the rain falls steadily.</p>

<p>&ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo; Jack says. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m calling now, aren&rsquo;t I?&rdquo;</p>

<p>(Bad move, Ali. Now he sounds defensive.) &ldquo;You know what I mean. I&rsquo;ve been sick for two weeks &mdash;&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;How are you feeling?&rdquo; he jumps in solicitously.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Shitty. Plus I have a hunch something&rsquo;s up with you.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;OK,&rdquo; he confesses. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s this girl. The one I told you about.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You mean what&rsquo;s-her-name? The twenty-eight-year-old?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Gwendolyn. She&rsquo;s almost twenty-nine.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;<em>Jack</em>.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;What? We had an agreement.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Ah, yes, the famous agreement, the one he makes with all his lovers. (Be cool, Ali.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. ) No, why the hell should I be cool? &ldquo;You&rsquo;re going out with someone named <em>Gwendolyn</em> who&rsquo;s <em>almost</em> twenty-nine, and you don&rsquo;t call me for two weeks while I have the flu: what&rsquo;s wrong with this fucking picture?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;See, I knew you would be upset.&rdquo; He sighs.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m not upset &mdash; I&rsquo;m homicidal. I just can&rsquo;t figure out which one of you to shoot first.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Look, I know she&rsquo;s too young for me. I know it won&rsquo;t last; she&rsquo;s leaving town in six months. But, for right now, she makes me happy, and I need to feel that way. I&rsquo;ve had a hard year.&rdquo;</p>

<p>There&rsquo;s not much I can argue with there. It&rsquo;s been hard years all around, for me and everyone else I know. We help to make it that way, with our desires and fears. I could be mad at Jack right now, but I&rsquo;m just as ambivalent as he is, and we both know it, so my self-righteousness sounds a little feeble.</p>

<p>Jack goes on explaining: &ldquo;She lives in my town, not an hour and a half away in a goddamn ghetto &mdash;&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I do not live in a ghetto!&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;All right, barrio, then. And she&rsquo;s comfortable and easy. We just enjoy our time together. You .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. you want things. I can see it in your face, even when you don&rsquo;t say it. And I can&rsquo;t give you those things. Do you hear me, Ali? I can&rsquo;t. And it hurts me not to be able to. Look, I&rsquo;m sorry.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh, great. You&rsquo;re <em>sorry</em>.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I really am. But I&rsquo;m also doing you a favor. No one wants you to be happy more than I do. I mean that. If I could find the guy who would do it, I would pay his plane fare from Alaska. Because you deserve it, Ali. We all do.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;re the last person I ever expected to spout New Age bullshit at me.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;The point is, you have to figure out where your happiness lies and go for it. You want a family? Go for a family. Maybe you won&rsquo;t get it, but I don&rsquo;t want you blaming me ten years from now when you&rsquo;re miserable and you don&rsquo;t have your dream.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">Damon opens packages of fluffy white bread, ham, and American cheese from Safeway. We&rsquo;re fixing sandwiches for today&rsquo;s group. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m worried about Cleo,&rdquo; he says as he sets out twenty slices of bread, assembly-line style, then starts slathering them with bright yellow mustard.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Why?&rdquo; I ask. &ldquo;Because she hasn&rsquo;t been to group lately?&rdquo; I follow behind him, laying one pale red slice of supermarket tomato and a watery leaf of iceberg lettuce on each sandwich.</p>

<p>&ldquo;She hasn&rsquo;t even been to school lately.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;What&rsquo;s the story?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know. I saw her hanging out by the steps with her buddies as I drove up. She was smoking.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll go out there.&rdquo;</p>

<p>At lunch, the boys play basketball and the girls hang out in little groups, their faces carefully made up. This year the style is light blue frosted eye shadow above thick black eyeliner, framed by a cascade of shellacked ringlets. It looks good on a fresh, young, sixteen-year-old face. Of course, everything does.</p>

<p>Most of the girls wear painted-on jeans and tube tops, but some of them &mdash; Cleopatra is one &mdash; wear baggy jeans and loose <span class="smallcaps">T</span>-shirts. I remember that game of concealing and showing off. I remember feeling one day like the queen of sexy and the next like the fattest creature ever to walk the earth.</p>

<p>I find Cleo by the steps, just as Damon said, cigarette in hand. She sheepishly grinds it out when she sees me. &ldquo;I was just holding it for a friend,&rdquo; she says, not expecting me even to pretend to believe it. Damon&rsquo;s right: she doesn&rsquo;t look good. There are dark circles under her eyes. I invite her to my office to talk.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ll come by in five minutes,&rdquo; she says.</p>

<p>I know she can&rsquo;t risk the embarrassment of trailing after me through the crowded lunchtime schoolyard. I also know that &ldquo;five minutes&rdquo; might mean never. I hate to let her go, but I have to act casual. So I slip back to my airless little closet of an office and wait.</p>

<p>Fifteen minutes later, to my surprise, Cleo comes strolling in. &ldquo;Got any pizza?&rdquo; she asks, sinking into the swivel chair and rolling back and forth just for the fun of it.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Nah, we&rsquo;ve got sandwiches. You hungry?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Not really,&rdquo; she says, avoiding my eyes. &ldquo;How much money you make at this job?&rdquo;</p>

<p>I laugh. &ldquo;Not enough.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You got to go to college to do this?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well, it helps. But experience is better. Why? You think you might want to be a counselor sometime?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, I&rsquo;d like to talk to kids.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;d be good at it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Silence. She looks away. Communicating with an adolescent is like crossing a river on a slippery log: any false step can land your ass in the water and make you look like a fool. But you can feel the kid silently calling out to you from the other side of the river, begging you not to give up.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I hear you haven&rsquo;t been coming to school lately. How long has it been?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I dunno.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Anything going on at home?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, my mama kicked me out again.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Any idea why?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I dunno. She has too many stupid rules.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Best leave that one alone for the moment. &ldquo;So, where are you sleeping?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;At my auntie&rsquo;s. But she say I can&rsquo;t stay long, because she don&rsquo;t have the room, and she be scared I&rsquo;ll get my cousin in trouble.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Are you worried about where to go next?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Would it be <span class="smallcaps">OK</span> .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. I mean, would you mind if I talked to your mom? Maybe we can straighten things out, if it was a misunderstanding or something.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Wasn&rsquo;t no misunderstanding. She want me out of there. She said so.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I look at her beautiful, closed-off face, still round with baby fat, and think, <em>Cleo, Cleo, Cleo</em>. I know for a fact that I&rsquo;m inadequate to this situation. But I also know that, for better or worse, I&rsquo;m the only one here.</p>

<p>&ldquo;So, do you want me to call your mom? Can I do that for you?&rdquo;</p>

<p>She shrugs. &ldquo;If you want to.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I do.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s a lie. I don&rsquo;t really want to call this strange woman and be a nosy counselor butting into her private relationship with her rebellious teenage daughter. But the raw, exhausted look in Cleo&rsquo;s eyes says, <em>Do something</em>, even if I don&rsquo;t know exactly what the best thing would be.</p>

<p>Cleo&rsquo;s mother returns my call while on her break at the bank. Her voice is heavy with fatigue. &ldquo;She in trouble again? I ain&rsquo;t seen her for three weeks.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;She&rsquo;s not in trouble with the law, if that&rsquo;s what you mean. But she&rsquo;s been skipping a lot of school, and we&rsquo;re concerned. She was doing so well this semester, but then everything seemed to go downhill about a month ago.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, well, I told her to stay in school, but I can&rsquo;t make her. She&rsquo;ll tell me she&rsquo;s going to school, and then she&rsquo;ll slip out and hang with her friends, getting into all kinds of trouble. I&rsquo;m so tired of her lies.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;She said you told her she couldn&rsquo;t stay at home anymore.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, I did. I&rsquo;ve got a ten-year-old, and I don&rsquo;t want her getting any wrong ideas. I don&rsquo;t know what she told you, but that girl will manipulate and lie until you don&rsquo;t even know up from down. You got any kids?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;No.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Best keep it that way. You don&rsquo;t even know what heartache is until you got a teenager.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">Tilden Park, in the hills above Berkeley, is warm and brown in late January. Prickly bits of thistle cling to our shoelaces as Norah, Elijah, and I edge across a leaf-littered log bridge.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Let&rsquo;s pretend we&rsquo;re Indians,&rdquo; I tell the kids. &ldquo;See how quietly you can step.&rdquo; Of course, the Ohlone and the Miwok didn&rsquo;t wear oversized Nikes with bright lights flashing on their pumped-up soles. Still, it feels good to invoke them.</p>

<p>We have already made our ritual visit to the petting zoo, where we fed limp shreds of lettuce to the pushy donkeys and patted the goat, with her smooth head and slotted black eyes and swollen milk bag hanging low between her legs like a water balloon about to burst. Now Elijah, who had to be unglued from his PlayStation before he could leave the house, has come alive again in the silence of the woods.</p>

<p>Norah sees the lizard first. (Or is it a newt?) He moves when prodded, turns over, and begins to crawl, lumbering slowly over her small pink palm. She squeals as his feet tickle her wrist.</p>

<p>Elijah snatches the lizard from Norah. At first, he was just entranced by it. Now he&rsquo;s seriously in love. &ldquo;Please, Ali, please, can we take him home? He has green eyes. He&rsquo;s looking at me! Look at his orange belly. Aw, he&rsquo;s so cute. I promise I&rsquo;ll take good care of him. I promise, I promise, I promise. Please, Ali, please please please.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Norah, who&rsquo;s used to Elijah taking things from her, is hugging the tall, scarred eucalyptus. She cranes her head back, studying the ragged bark hanging off the trunk in fragrant strips. A few feet above her head, lovers&rsquo; initials are carved into the tree&rsquo;s flesh. &ldquo;Why they do that?&rdquo; she asks.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Because they loved each other and wanted to make a mark to last forever.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;&nbsp;&rsquo;Member when we used to come here when we was little?&rdquo; she asks, breaking my heart. I used to bring them here every week &mdash; here, or to the beach, or to the flea market, where Grace and I would pick through piles of old clothes while the kids tugged at our sleeves and begged for plastic guns and cheap mermaid necklaces. Now that I live across town, I sometimes let a month or more go by without making the time to visit. How strange and painful is this role of being not-quite-auntie, not quite there, not quite anywhere.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Hey, Ali,&rdquo; Norah interrupts my reverie, &ldquo;what happened to that Bill Clinton guy?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Bill Clinton?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, that guy you brought over on Christmas to see us,&rdquo; Elijah chimes in. &ldquo;With the gray hair.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Bill Clinton, huh? Jack will get a kick out of this when he hears about it &mdash; sorry excuse for an ex-boyfriend that he is. &ldquo;Oh, I don&rsquo;t know, honey. I&rsquo;m not seeing him much lately.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Elijah is concerned. &ldquo;You had a fight, huh? What happened? You all was <em>talkin</em>,&rsquo; right?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;No, we didn&rsquo;t fight. It&rsquo;s just .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. sometimes people want different things.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I know,&rdquo; Norah announces loudly, putting her hands on her hips and rotating her head around the way she has seen the girls do on <span class="smallcaps">TV</span>. &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t have to explain it to <em>me</em>: mens!&rdquo;</p>

<p>I laugh, and we continue trooping through the woods, Elijah bearing the lizard reverently on his open palm like a devotee carrying an offering. &ldquo;Please, Ali, please please please!&rdquo; he repeats, on the not unreasonable theory that I will say yes just to get him to shut up. It has worked before. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll take <em>good</em> care of him, I promise!&rdquo;</p>

<p>I have seen the signs warning people not to remove any creatures from the park. I understand the importance of protecting wild animals, of keeping what wilderness we have left as natural as possible. I have a pretty good idea what the odds are of this lizard&rsquo;s survival in an enthusiastic ten-year-old&rsquo;s grasp. But I&rsquo;m faltering. I try a weak argument: &ldquo;How would you like it if an alien came down and grabbed you and took you up to his planet?&rdquo;</p>

<p>Elijah is way ahead of me: &ldquo;I would like it! I&rsquo;d want to see what his planet looked like!&rdquo;</p>

<p>I weigh the life of a small brown lizard with green eyes, a rust-colored belly, and sweet suckers on its feet against the ardent desire on Elijah&rsquo;s face. These are the last days of his childhood. How many more times will I have a chance to kindle so great a joy with so small a thing? How long will it be before Elijah becomes like Malcolm, jaded by the cheap happiness of a ten-dollar sack of weed? How long before Norah&rsquo;s eyes are as empty and tired as Cleo&rsquo;s?</p>

<p>&ldquo;OK,&rdquo; I agree weakly.</p>

<p>Elijah&rsquo;s face lights up like a firecracker. &ldquo;Yippee!&rdquo; He hands the poor lizard to Norah and does one, two, three cartwheels in a row. &ldquo;Ali, I bet you don&rsquo;t know how many muscles in the human body. Two hundred and six!&rdquo; And then he is off, unable to contain himself a moment longer, zigzagging and whooping through the hushed woods.</p>

<p>Later, after I&rsquo;ve bought them ice cream, dropped them off at their house, and driven across town to my own peaceful den, the phone rings. It&rsquo;s Grace:</p>

<p>&ldquo;Ali, what is this thing Elijah&rsquo;s got? I put him in water, but he like to drown. Called three pet stores, and they couldn&rsquo;t tell me nothing. Finally, I called this place that&rsquo;s just for lizards. They say he&rsquo;s a newt. And he don&rsquo;t eat lettuce; he eat insects. I ain&rsquo;t got no insects this time of year.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m sorry, Grace. I knew it was the wrong thing to do, but he begged and begged.&rdquo;</p>

<p>She laughs. &ldquo;I know how Elijah is, but you got to say no to him.&rdquo;</p>

<p>As always, I am humbled by her common sense. Grace takes the time to call three pet stores and a herpetarium because what passes between her and these children is not about happiness. It&rsquo;s about love: a love so big it encompasses happiness and unhappiness; a love that doesn&rsquo;t end with keeping these young ones clothed and fed, but extends outward to all the places her children wander, and to all the creatures they bring home.</p>
														</div>


				
